{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"eb52e92c-2f06-4fe7-aa6f-38e1ca8ade38","content":"You don't need the SDK. Download the **standalone `dotnet-trace`** directly into the container:\n\n```bash\n# From inside the container (or via docker exec)\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o /tmp/dotnet-trace\nchmod +x /tmp/dotnet-trace\n```\n\nThen collect a CPU trace:\n\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\n/tmp/dotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU sampling trace\n/tmp/dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling -o /tmp/trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Other options to get it in:**\n- **`docker cp`** — download it on the host, then `docker cp dotnet-trace <container>:/tmp/`\n- **Dockerfile layer** — add the `curl` line above to your Dockerfile for debugging images\n\nThe resulting `.nettrace` file can be analyzed with **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope** (`dotnet-trace convert --format speedscope`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ae1add53-90a5-4ec7-9f3f-2e561cca876e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a Linux container that doesn't have the .NET SDK installed, to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app experiencing high CPU.\n\nThis is a general knowledge question about .NET diagnostics tooling. I can answer this directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nKey points:\n1. `dotnet-trace` is a .NET global tool, but you can also get it as a standalone download\n2. For containers without the SDK, you can download the standalone version\n3. You can also sidecar it or copy it in\n\nLet me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":414,"requestId":"2166:3D3F15:3BB1FA:45DD21:69F00D47"},"id":"52ffa1be-8b2e-4f38-99ac-7e2eed905a4d","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:28:50.220Z","parentId":"8bf71cea-289a-4f98-999e-9e74c50292c5"}
